  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>1.16 billion people worldwide have migraine. Not bad headaches — migraine: a neurological condition that sends people vomiting in darkened rooms, that wipes out days in the middle of careers and childhoods, that is invisible to everyone who doesn't have it and debilitating to everyone who does. By disability, it ranks second among adults under 60, behind only stroke. First among children. In 2025, after what neurologists called the biggest pharmacological breakthrough in decades, the best answer medicine has for most of them is: take this monthly injection and hope your attack frequency drops by half.</p>
  <p>The word "cure" does not appear in any current migraine treatment guideline. Nobody expects it to. The question worth asking is why — and who benefits from that remaining true.</p>
</section>

<section id="mechanism" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Mechanism Was Always the Easy Part</h2>
  <p>The CGRP drugs are real. That bears stating plainly, because honest scrutiny of a funding ecosystem can look, from a distance, like dismissal of the science. It isn't.</p>
  <p>In the 1980s, researchers identified calcitonin gene-related peptide as a key neuropeptide released during migraine attacks — a potent vasodilator flooding into the bloodstream when the trigeminal system fires. By the early 2000s, human provocation studies had confirmed it: infuse CGRP into a migraine patient, watch a migraine follow. The target was obvious. Four monoclonal antibodies followed — erenumab, fremanezumab, galcanezumab, eptinezumab — plus a class of small-molecule gepants. Unlike the old preventive therapies, all borrowed from other conditions (anticonvulsants, antihypertensives, antidepressants), these were designed from the start for migraine. The science behind them is real and the mechanism is not disputed.</p>
  <p>Five-year open-label extension data on erenumab, published in <em>The Lancet Neurology</em> in 2023, showed sustained reductions in monthly migraine days. For many patients, these drugs are genuinely life-changing. The American Headache Society's 2024 position statement was not wrong to describe the cumulative evidence as substantially greater than that for any established migraine preventive therapy.</p>
  <p>It's also a lower bar than it sounds.</p>
</section>

<section id="guidelines" class="reveal">
  <h2>The People Who Wrote the Guidelines</h2>
  <p>In March 2024, the AHS released an updated position statement elevating CGRP-targeting therapies to first-line status for migraine prevention — removing the requirement that patients first fail cheaper drugs. The clinical logic appears reasonable and the evidence supports it, though critics like independent neurologists argue it overlooks access barriers and prioritizes patented drugs over proven generics. The downstream effects were large. Express Scripts and Cigna subsequently expanded coverage, reaching approximately 30 million additional patients.</p>
  <p>The lead author was Andrew Charles, MD, then-president of the AHS. His disclosures: compensated consultant for Amgen, Eli Lilly, eNeura, and Lundbeck. Three of those four companies sell CGRP-targeting therapies. The other authors' conflicts ran to hundreds of words. Peter Goadsby, among the world's most cited migraine researchers and a co-author, listed personal fees from Abbvie, Amgen, Eli Lilly, Lundbeck, Novartis, Pfizer, Sanofi, and Teva, among others.</p>
  <p>The institution itself: a Medscape report on the statement noted, in a single sentence, that the AHS "receives support from industry for educational programming, research, and advocacy," from companies including AbbVie, Amgen, Eli Lilly, Lundbeck, Pfizer, and Teva — the same companies whose products the guidelines now recommend first. The companies had, per the statement, "no direct or indirect involvement in the development and writing." That disclaimer is technically accurate. It is also structurally incomplete. You do not need to direct the writing when you have spent years funding the culture.</p>
  <p>The same financial architecture runs through the pivotal trials. The five-year erenumab safety and efficacy data was funded by Amgen and Novartis Pharma, manufacturers of erenumab. The phase 3 studies that established the field's benchmarks were industry-funded. The review articles shaping clinical consensus listed author conflicts with advisory boards at AbbVie, Eli Lilly, Lundbeck, Novartis, Pfizer, and Teva.</p>
  <p>This is not a conspiracy. It is a funding ecosystem. When NIH investment in migraine fails to match its disease burden — a 2024 commentary in <em>Headache</em> called this "the elephant in the room" — industry fills the vacuum. It funds what it can patent. The questions that get asked are the ones with patentable answers.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The questions that get asked are the ones with patentable answers."</p></aside>

<section id="responders" class="reveal">
  <h2>What Fifty Percent Response Actually Means</h2>
  <p>The standard efficacy benchmark for CGRP drugs is the "≥50% responder rate" — the share of patients who achieve at least a 50% reduction in monthly migraine days. In pivotal trials, this ranged from roughly 42 to 59% for the monoclonal antibodies. Which means, depending on which drug and which trial, between 41 and 58% of patients don't reach that threshold.</p>
  <p>There is also the question of what the threshold measures. A patient with 15 migraine days per month who achieves a 50% response still has 7 or 8 migraine days per month. That is a meaningful improvement. It is not resolution of the condition. It is management of a chronic neurological state, indefinitely, at approximately $640 to $740 per monthly dose without insurance. Elizabeth Loder, a Harvard neurologist who disclosed no industry ties, told Medscape that the manufacturer coupons offsetting this cost reach only patients with commercial insurance. Medicare and Medicaid patients are on their own.</p>
  <p>In patients who have already failed two to four prior preventive therapies — exactly the patients for whom clinicians most need something new — three industry-funded trials found that only 30 to 38% achieved that ≥50% threshold in a 12-week window. Across multiple meta-analyses and real-world cohorts, the proportion of patients who don't respond adequately to CGRP therapies sits at roughly 40%. The field's explanation for why is still largely theoretical.</p>
  <p>Migraine is mechanistically heterogeneous. CGRP is one driver, not the only one. The near-exclusive focus on the CGRP pathway in both commercial funding and published research is what a monoculture looks like. It is not necessarily what the biology looks like.</p>
</section>

<div class="data-callout reveal"><p><strong>On the responder-rate benchmark:</strong> A ≥50% reduction in monthly migraine days is the field's standard measure of treatment success — but it means patients still experience half their previous migraine burden. For someone with 20 migraine days per month at baseline, "responding" to treatment may mean 10 migraine days per month remains. The outcome measure itself reflects a management goal, not a curative one, and shapes how progress in the field is defined and reported.</p></div>

<section id="safety" class="reveal">
  <h2>Five Years Is Not a Lifetime</h2>
  <p>CGRP does more than trigger migraine pain. It is one of the body's most potent vasodilators, with protective roles in cardiovascular stress, resistance to hypertension, wound healing, and bone metabolism. A 2016 analysis in <em>Trends in Pharmacological Sciences</em> raised concerns about CGRP's protective roles, but more recent 2023-2025 reviews highlight unresolved risks in vascular patients excluded from trials, underscoring the need for updated independent research.</p>
  <p>Current data from industry-funded studies appear reassuring in the short term, but they exclude high-risk patients and lack independent long-term validation. A study of 88 patients with stable angina found no aggravation of myocardial ischemia after a high-dose erenumab infusion. The five-year extension data showed no clear cardiac signal. A 2025 analysis of FDA adverse-event reporting data found signals worth monitoring, but no alarming pattern. A review published the same year in <em>Neurology</em> concluded the safety profile looked favorable for patients without major vascular risk factors — while noting that evidence remains limited for those with established vascular disease, who were largely excluded from the registration trials.</p>
  <p>That last point matters more than it is usually given credit for. Patients with migraine already carry elevated cardiovascular risk. The population most plausibly exposed to long-term CGRP blockade is not a low-risk trial cohort. Five years of post-marketing data in selected patients is a beginning. It is not a settled answer.</p>
  <p>The AHS's 2024 position statement called the long-term safety record "remarkable." Reassuring would be accurate. Remarkable forecloses a question that responsible medicine should keep open.</p>
</section>

<section id="pacap" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Next Breakthrough Looks Familiar</h2>
  <p>For the roughly 40% of patients CGRP therapies don't adequately help, the field has a candidate: PACAP. Pituitary adenylate cyclase-activating polypeptide is another neuropeptide implicated in migraine — it can provoke attacks when infused into patients, and it acts through receptor targets that CGRP therapies don't reach. A 2025 controlled trial confirmed that PACAP-induced migraine attacks proceed via pathways entirely independent of CGRP, which means the two drug classes would work on mechanistically distinct patient populations. That's a genuine scientific finding with real clinical implications.</p>
  <p>In 2024, a phase 2 trial of bocunebart — a monoclonal antibody against PACAP, published in the <em>New England Journal of Medicine</em> — showed 6.2 fewer monthly migraine days versus 4.2 on placebo. Modest. Real. Comparable to early CGRP trial effect sizes.</p>
  <p>Bocunebart is being developed by Lundbeck, whose personnel appear in the conflict disclosures of multiple migraine researchers whose work shapes clinical consensus, and whose organization is a documented AHS financial supporter. The drug is patentable. The guideline bodies that will eventually evaluate it are the same ones funded by the industry that produces it.</p>
  <p>None of this means the drug won't work. It means the research apparatus for the second most disabling neurological condition on earth is entirely contained within a pharmaceutical model. The question that never gets funded — what non-patentable mechanisms might drive migraine in the patients neither CGRP nor PACAP therapies reach? — is not unanswerable. It is just unattractive to the people writing the checks.</p>
</section>

<section id="structure" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Research Agenda Has an Owner</h2>
  <p>The AHS's 2024 position statement is a reasonable document built on real evidence. Its principal authors are paid consultants for the manufacturers of the drugs it recommends. The five-year erenumab data is genuinely informative — funded by the companies that sell erenumab. The PACAP advance is a legitimate scientific finding — its lead investigators disclose fees from Lundbeck, AbbVie, and Pfizer. None of this is hidden. The disclosures are there, paragraphs long, at the foot of every paper.</p>
  <p>The problem is not individual. Individual corruption would be easier to address. The problem is structural. When public funding for the second most disabling neurological condition on earth falls systematically short of its disease burden, when no alternative funding infrastructure exists for research without a commercial endpoint, the pharmaceutical model fills the gap completely — and it funds what it can sell.</p>
  <p>Reducing attack frequency by half, indefinitely, in the patients it works for — that is a product. Determining why roughly 40% don't respond, in a research program indifferent to whether the answer leads to a drug — that is basic science. Basic science at this scale requires independent public funding. There is not enough of it.</p>
  <p>The questions the field should be asking — why migraine is mechanistically heterogeneous, what drives attacks in the patients no neuropeptide antibody reaches, whether "migraine" is in fact several distinct conditions requiring distinct research programs — require nobody to produce a drug at the end. That is also precisely why they go unasked.</p>
  <p>Nobody with power over the migraine research agenda has an incentive to change this. Not the companies. Not the professional societies that run on company money. Not the guideline authors whose consulting income is entangled with the industry whose products the guidelines rank.</p>
  <p>The system is not broken. It is working exactly as designed.</p>
</section>

